## Ansible Playbook Integration

### Backup Playbook Example

```yaml — - name: Backup Homelab Infrastructure

hosts: localhost
connection: local
gather_facts: false
vars_files:
  - ../vars/vault.yml  # Loads encrypted passwords

tasks:
  - name: Backup Gitea database
    shell: |
      TIMESTAMP=$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)
      docker exec postgres pg_dump -U jireland gitea > /opt/backups/gitea-db-${TIMESTAMP}.sql
    delegate_to: apps.lab.local
    environment:
      PGPASSWORD: "{{ vault_postgres_password }}"  # Uses vault variable

```

No hardcoded passwords in playbook. Password sourced from encrypted vault.yml.

## Security Best Practices

### Protection Mechanisms

✅ Ansible Vault: - Encrypted with AES256 - Password stored separately - Version controlled (encrypted state)

✅ .env Files: - 0600 permissions (owner only) - Not version controlled (.gitignored) - Regenerated from vault (not edited manually)

✅ Vault Password: - Stored in Vaultwarden - 0600 permissions on .vault_pass - Not version controlled (.gitignored)

✅ Vaultwarden: - Master password stored offline - HTTPS encrypted access - Regular backups

### What Never Gets Committed

❌ `.env` files (plaintext passwords) ❌ `.vault_pass` (vault password) ❌ Decrypted vault.yml ❌ Backup files with data ❌ Private keys ❌ Database dumps

✅ Can be committed: - Encrypted vault.yml (still encrypted) - docker-compose.yml (uses ${VARIABLES}) - Playbooks (use vault_variables) - Documentation

### Access Control

Who Can Access: - Ansible Vault: Anyone with vault password - .env files: Root and jireland user on hosts - Vaultwarden: Anyone with master password

Physical Security: - mgmt.lab.local hosts Ansible control node - Access to mgmt = access to automation - SSH key-based authentication required - Firewall rules limit access

## Backup and Recovery

### What Gets Backed Up

Nightly Backups Include: - Ansible Vault (encrypted vault.yml) - version controlled - Vaultwarden database - included in Docker volumes backup - .env files - backed up with /opt/docker/ directory

Offline Backups: - Vaultwarden master password - secure offline storage - Ansible vault password - stored in Vaultwarden + offline backup - SSH private keys - encrypted offline storage

### Recovery Scenarios

Lost Ansible Vault Password:

1. Retrieve from Vaultwarden (“Ansible Vault Password” entry) 2. If Vaultwarden also inaccessible, use offline backup 3. Worst case: Recreate vault.yml with new passwords

Lost Vaultwarden Master Password:

No recovery possible. All passwords must be rotated manually: 1. Reset all database passwords 2. Reset all service admin passwords 3. Recreate Vaultwarden database 4. Re-enter all passwords manually

Prevention: Store master password in secure offline location.

Corrupted vault.yml:

1. Restore from git history (still encrypted) 2. Restore from nightly backup 3. Decrypt and verify contents

Lost .env Files:

Regenerate from Ansible Vault:

```bash ansible-playbook /opt/ansible/playbooks/generate-env-files.yml ```

## Troubleshooting

### Ansible Vault Errors

“Vault password incorrect”

Cause: Wrong password in .vault_pass or manual entry

Solution: ```bash # Verify vault password in Vaultwarden # Update .vault_pass file nano /opt/ansible/.vault_pass chmod 600 /opt/ansible/.vault_pass ```

“Vault file corrupted”

Cause: File corruption or manual editing error

Solution: ```bash # Restore from git history git log /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml git checkout COMMIT_HASH – /opt/ansible/vars/vault.yml

# Or restore from backup ```

### Docker Container Errors

“Access denied for user”

Cause: Password mismatch between .env and database

Solution: 1. Check password in Ansible Vault matches database 2. Regenerate .env files 3. Or reset database password to match .env

“Cannot start container - environment variable not set”

Cause: .env file missing or empty variable

Solution: ```bash # Verify .env exists ls -la /opt/docker/.env

# Regenerate .env ansible-playbook /opt/ansible/playbooks/generate-env-files.yml

# Verify variable populated cat /opt/docker/.env | grep VARIABLE_NAME ```

### .env File Issues

“.env file not being read”

Cause: .env must be in same directory as docker-compose.yml

Solution: ```bash # Verify location ls -la /opt/docker/.env ls -la /opt/docker/docker-compose.yml

# Both must be in /opt/docker/ ```

“Permission denied reading .env”

Cause: Incorrect file permissions

Solution: ```bash sudo chmod 600 /opt/docker/.env sudo chown jireland:jireland /opt/docker/.env ```

